        5
      ],
      "solution": "<p><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong>Ans. C. Naïve B cells</strong></span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong>Option C:</strong></span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong><u>Explanation:</u></strong></span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong>Ig genes </strong>of some CLL/SLL are somatically <strong>hypermutated, </strong>whereas others are not, suggesting that the <strong>cell of origin</strong> may be either a <strong>post-germinal center memory B cell </strong>or a <strong>naive B cell</strong>. It is <strong>not </strong>originating from<strong> progenitor B cell or mature B cell.</strong></span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong><u>Educational Objective:</u></strong></span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\">The<strong> cell </strong>of origin for<strong> CLL/SLL is the naive B cell</strong>, which may or may not undergo<strong> somatic hypermutation, </strong>suggesting that <strong>CLL/SLL </strong>can arise from a<strong> pre-germinal center B cell.</strong></span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>(Ref: Robbins 10th/e p597)</strong></span></p>",
